Humans grew up learning that the progress we have made came at the cost of nature. Almost all scientists, writers, and lecturers agreed that there would never be a win-win for both the environment and humans. For example, in popular culture, movies like Avatar and WALL-E showed the mass destruction humans bring to the world. 
Because of this, more people tended to believe that the Earth will soon be uninhabitable, and started investing in space exploration. Take Jeff Bezos as an example, he even stated that it was necessary to go to space if humans still wanted a prosperous civilization. However, some scientists disagreed by saying the space was more dangerous and more difficult to be maintained than the Earth was. 
That was why the author suggests that we need a different story, one that could encourage people to live in harmony with nature, and the movie was Black Panther. Wakanda, the fictional city in the movie, is the most technologically advanced place yet also the best at maintaining the environment. Inspired by existing African cultures, the filmmakers picture a modern city with trees and plants all over the area and without suburbs that experience heavy pollution. Although the establishment of Wakanda depends on vibranium, a fictional metal that powers the city, other organic infrastructures suggest that Wakanda will remain sustainable even without the metal. With this being said, Wakanda gives people hope because it shows that it indeed is possible to protect the world while improving peopleâs lives, and the author believes that this kind of story is what the world needs in order to enact change.

Literary realism started in the 1800s, rejecting Romantic ideas. They thought that Romanticism was too exotic and detached from reality. As realist writers want to portray reality, it mainly started in the form of newspapers, as they are the best medium to describe and write about something in a most unbiased and truthful way. They used realistic diction to try to accurately depict the subjects that theyâre writing about, mostly mid-lower class people or war. Modernism, on the other hand, was a reaction to the horrors of the Great War(WW I). As WW I ravaged across Europe, it also shattered peopleâs original Victorian ideals. Modernists began to reject tradition and absolute truths. They showed their rebellious nature through writing about taboo subjects and writing in experimental formats.

Logos 
In âNarrative of the Life of Frederick Douglassâ, the author Frederick Douglass utilizes logos to support his claim that slavery is horrific. By applying logos in the passage, Douglass shows his ability to reveal logic and reason in the text. In the part when he ran away from Mr. Covey and looked for help from his former master Thomas, he writes that he is covered in blood from head to foot and that only âa heart of ironâ will not be moved by it. When he mentions how Thomas refused to accept Douglass' appeal, Douglass shows how slaves were seen as property during the 1800s. The logic he employs here is that his appearance âcan affect anyone but one with a heart of iron.â Master Thomas was not affected, which means that he was a cold-blooded man. This is an evidence that proves that slaveholders did not recognize slaves as human. Therefore, Douglassâ audience will agree with his claim that slavery is evil.

This year I got selected to be a Taiwan ambassador for Hugh OâBrian Youth World Leadership Congress. The congress took place in Chicago. This was the first time I went abroad without my parents, which made the experience even more significant. When I first got there, I was very nervous because I had never been in a situation that I had to speak English 24/7. I was afraid if I said something wrong, people would make fun of me. This happens in the real world, but not HOBY. I could be the best version of myself, and get to know many other outstanding people.
	Instead of writing about the whole event, I am just going to share one activity we did throughout the conference. It was called the Global Snapshot. It was basically a presentation given by the ambassadors of different country. Yet, it wasnât limited to where we are from. For example, one of my group members has lived in the US for more than ten years, but he is actually from India. So he represented India in the activity. He even showed us traditional Indian dance. Other ambassadors such as the one from Brazil, taught us Samba, and the ones from Mexico sang the most passionately. It was a very interesting activity because they were all the first people I knew from those countries. Seeing my friends on stage representing their own countries made me feel so happy. I did the Snapshot, too. I was very proud of myself my fellow ambassadors, and the ambassadors of Hong Kong, because we talked about the issues in our homes which no foreigners seemed to know before our presentation. Everyone stood up and applauded. Also, after the presentation, many people came to me and showed their support. I felt amazing.
	The HOBY WLC was hands down the best experience Iâve ever had. I had the best group, met the best people, and had the best time. Words can never be enough to explain HOBY. Everything was possible in HOBY. Everyone was so kind and loving. I felt the most invincible when I was in WLC. This once in a life time experience has changed me in lots of ways. Hopefully I could keep motivate myself to bring the change and spread my love to the community. 
	If I could just tell you one thing, I would say that stay OUTSTANDING.
